                    <lb n="3"/><w n="25">Σίμων</w> <w n="30">Κα</w> <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character" n="35"/>
                    <lb n="4"/><w lemma="ὁ" rend="ὁ " n="40">ὁ</w> <w lemma="ἱερεύς" rend="ἱερεὺς" n="45">ἱερεὺς</w> <w n="50">Ἀ<unclear>ρ</unclear><supplied reason="lost" cert="low">σινόης</supplied></w> <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character" n="55"/>
                    <lb n="5"/><w n="60">Ἀφροδίτης</w> <orig n="65">Σ<unclear>Τ</unclear></orig><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character" n="70"/>
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                    <app loc="1">
                        <note>Ἰσχυωνίδας in ed.pr. appears to have been a misprint, and was corrected by Bingen.</note>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <p>To Osiris, Ischonidas son of Timon, a Cretan from Phaistos, (dedicated this) in accordance with a command.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>Fraser derived an Alexandrian origin for this otherwise undocumented dedication from its fine lettering and marble support. The dedicant is a Cretan, Ischonidas from Phaistos, perhaps a mercenary, who made this offering to Osiris from a divine command, perhaps received through a dream or oracle (Chaniotis 2000, 210).</p>
            </div>
